{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_oliver_ver01/data/sn83045462/00280600593/1930092701/0223.xml":{"full_text":"A-2\nDAWES SEES 1931\nDEPRESSION END\nAmbassador Tells Irish Busi\nness of World Is Now\nRecuperating.\nB\u00bb tin Awoeisted Prcn.\nBELFAST, Northern Ireland. Sep\ntember 37.\u2014Ambv**dor Pawes, speak- j\nInf u (ueat o t honor at an official\nluncheon at th# city Hall today, pre-\ndieted the end of the current world- j\nwide Industrial and trade depression by\nthe Summer or Fall of next year.\n\u2019The business fool of 1939 was he\nwho had no fear,\" he sfld.\nThe Ambassadors address was an\nanalysis of \"present world-wide indus\ntrial and trade depression, its cause\nand Its probable duration.\u201d\nGen. Dawes said he would not fall\nInto the common error of travelers of dis\ncussing questions of local industry, but\nthat in Belfast, which is a center of\nworld-wide business, he could properly\ndiscuss the present world-wide depres\nsion, since, as nearly everywhere else,\nit is having its serious local effect.\nAmbassador's Address.\nThe Ambassador's address practically\nht full follows:\n\"A world depression in business is\ndue always to sudden change in the at\ntitude of the world\u2019s peoples. This\nchanged attitude is often explained in\ndifferent countries as being the result\nof diverse causes, including unwise na\ntional policies, undue speculation, over\nproduction, underconsumption and poli\ntical or social upheavals.\n\"These, however, are more the ef\nfects of this change of general attitude\nthan the causes of It. It is often easier\nto conclude that one catastrophe or\nerror in business is the cause of the\nfollowing one, rather than that both\noriginate from one underlying cause.\n\u201cIn the United States, for Instance, as\nwell as elsewhere, a major depression\nin business has always been preceded a.\nfew months before by a stock panic\ninduced by overspeculation. Many\nhave assumed that the collapse of the\nstock market caused the later depres\nsion. Many have assumed, too, that\nthis correct forecasting of business\ntrends by stock speculators is evidence\nof the composite intelligence of the\nspeculating class.\nCaused by Same Thing.\n\u2018'Nothing could be more untrue, for\nnot only is the speculating class as a\nwhole no wiser than these ip other\nbusinesses, but no intellectual judgment\nof the future can always prove to be\nright and in this case general unloading\nof stocks months before general busi\nness is materially affected always oc\ncurs. The truth is that stock market\ndepression and the following business\ndepression are both caused by the same\nthing\u2014a fundamental change in the\nattitude of the average man resulting\nfrom a sudden loss of confidence on his\npart, the first public manifestation of\n-which occurs on the Stock Exchange.\n\"The reasons why the Stock Exchange\ngives this first evidence of a change in\ngeneral attitude are simple. Business\non the Stock Exchange is transacted\nunder unique conditions conducive to\nalmost immediate public registration of\n-general lack of confidence In values.\n-On the Stock Exchange when confi\n-denee in the future is rampant every\n-facility exists for speculators to get\n-easily into debt, an<f in proportion to\n-the thinness of their margin and larger\namount of stocks they carry upon given\n-capita! invested as margin the larger\ndo they compute their respective profits.\nContrarywise, when their optimism\nfalters, the quicker will they run from\nprospective lose necessarily proportion\nately as large.\n\u201cThe man with merchandise to sell,\nran the other hand, when he oommenees\nto loee confidence in values, will dis\npose of it gradually. He is net gen\nrerally under the necessity when the\nmarket drops \u00bbf immediately putting\n:up additional margins of security to\nrhis creditors if he prefers not to sell\nait then. When the market slackens\ndoes net have to fear being sold out\n:bv somebody else if he prefers to take\n'his own time in selling.\nLessens More Abrupt,\n\"Moreover, in general business, so\nmuch of which is concerned with sup\nplying of human necessities, there is\n'a greater continuance in demand and,\nin consequence, in timet of depression,\nra slower market decline than in stocks\ndemand, for which the lessons are more\nNevertheless, the fundamental\ncause of the decline in both is the\nsame.\n\u201cLet us consider this fundamental\ncause. Comments of learned economists\ndiffer so widely in respect to it and the\nprobable time of continuation of the\npresent world-wide business depression,\nthat we laymen may be excused for\nseeking simpler explanations. The\nqualities of composite mankind are but\nqualities of the average individual com\nposing it.\n\u201cAs the average man in his personal\nor business activities occasionally de\nparts from the usual, so does mankind.\nAs a man sometimes cuts loose from\nsafe business moorings so does man\nkind. As a man sometimes embarks\n-upon unknown and dangerous seas of\nspeculation and unsound enterprise, so\ndoes mankind, and what then happens\nto a man happens to mankind.\n\u201cWe don't know why s man goes\nwrong, but we have no difficulty in\nknowing when it is thus with mankind.\nAfter a hectic period induced by re\ngrettatole combination of overconfi\ndence and misdirected energy reaction\nand a return to a normal view of things\ncauses the first business collapse, then\na period of stagnation and then a\nperiod of recuperation.\nIn Stage of Recuperation.\n\u2018\"lhe business of mankind is now in\na stage of recuperation. We know that\nIn a general way under the law of\naction and reaction periods of under\nactivity In business are somewhat pro\nportional in length to periods of ac\ntivity preceding them. That time is\nconsiderably over a year behind us when\nthe public suddenly turned over from\nexhiliratkm and that confidence in the\nfuture which is the basis of prosperity\nto that lack of confidence which is\nthe basis of business depression.\n\u201cI do not think that the business of\nthe world left its normal trend earlier\nthan in 1937, two years before the col\nlapse of prices in 1939 on the leading\nstock exchanges of most nations. If\n-I am right in this, other things being\nequal, may we not hope to see normal\ntrend of world business resumed by\nBummer or Fall of next year, which\nwill mark the end of the after two\nyear period?\n\u201cExceptional local conditions may in\nthis or that country retard or ad\nvance the healing effect of returning\nworld business confidence, but nothing\nU more certain than the ooming busi\nness recovery. The business fool of\n1929 was he who had no fear. The\nfool now is he who has no hope.\u201d\n\u201cFine Raw Material.\u201d\nAfter analysing the Industrial and\ncommercial situation, Gen. Dawes told\nthe luncheon party of distinguished\nguests that Americans have a particu\nlar interest and profound respect for\n-Northern Ireland, not only because of\nits big industrial activities, such as\nlinen manufacturing and ship building,\nbut especially because out of the total\nt output of Presidents of the United\nr States about 40 per cent have been of\nScottish-Irish descent, namey. Jeffer\nson, Madison, Monroe, Jackson, Polk,\nTaylor, Buchanan, Johnson, Grant\nHayes, Arthur, Harrison and McKinley\n\u201cWe thus recognise you.\u201d he said,\n-.\u201cnot only as great exporters of fin\nished products, but of the finest raw\nmaterial as well.\"\nIn proposing a toast to the American\nj. Ambassador, sir William Coates, the\nI Death Is Probed\nHA-*..,\u2014 -ga ,*m\nMRS. E. L. M. ARCHEY,\nAssistant counsel of the Shipping IffntN.\nwho was found dead in her apartment\nthis morninfr under cireumstanoea indi\ncating she bad fainted while shout to\nlight a stove and had hoen asphyxiated\nfrom the open jet.\nCANNON PROBERS\nSOON TO BE NAMED\nBishop Ainsworth to An\nnounce Committee of Clergy\nmen in Two Weeks.\nBy the Associated Press.\nDr. Forrest J. Prettyman of Baltimore\nsaid today a committee of clergymen\nto investigate charges against Bishop\nJames cannon. Jr., of the Methodist\nEpiscopal Church. South, was likely to\nbe named \u201cwithin two weeks\u201d by Bishop\nW. N. Ainsworth, president of the\nchurch\u2019s College of Bishops.\nThe charges were sent to Bishop\nAinsworth by Dr. Prettyman, Dr. J. T.\nMas ten, Richmond; Dr. Costen J. Har\nrell. Richmond, and Dr. I. P. Martin,\nAbingdon, Va.\nDr. Prettyman, here attending the\nBaltimore Conference of his church,\nsaid today they had no desire to rush,\nbut intended to see the investigation\ncarried through. Ha mads public a\nletter from Dr. Martin, which said\nstudy had convinced him of the cor\nrectness of the aetion in filing the\ncharges under the law of the Southern\nMethodist Chureh.\nAnswer to Bishop.\nThe letter was in answer to a state\nment by Bis he a Cannon, received by\nthe Associated ftsrss by radio from the\nS. 8. American legion, on which he la\nreturning to this country from Braril,\nin which he Questioned the legality of\nthe procedure against him.\nThe churchmen have declined to re\nveal the charges against Cannon, but\nPrettyman said today they included\n\u201ceverything that has been discussed in\nthe public press, and mere.\u201d\nDr Martin's letter said:\n\u201cI find that the law (of the chureh)\nu It had stood from 1170 was amended\nin 1884. Prior to 1194 the law was,\n\u2018Three traveling ciders shall eall upon\nhim (a bishop) and carefully inquire\ninto the ease, and if they believe him\nguilty, they shall report the matter to\nanother bishop.\u2019 in 1894 the law waa\namended to road as at present.\nChanges es the Law.\n\u201cYou will see at one# that instead of\nthe three traveling elders being required\nto call upon the Bishop, as previously,\nthe law as amended changes this to\n\u201cafter notice to him.\u2019\u2019 Then again,\nunder the old law the elders were re\nquired to \u201cbelieve him guilty.\" Under\nthe present law the elders arc required\nto \"believe an investigation neoessary.\u201d\nThe other elders associated in the\ncharges against Bishop Cannon both\nattended the Baltimore Conference es\nthe churches here.\nDr. Harrell addressed the conference\nyesterday, and returned to his home\ntoday. Dr. Masten visited the confer\nence yesterday, departing today. Pretty\nman said they did not confer with re\ngard to the charges.\nKINCHELOE RESIGNS\nTO TAKE COURT POST\nKentucky Representative Also'\nQuits as Democratic Nominee\nfor Re-election.\n(From the I 10 Xdmsn es YMtardsr'a Star.)\nBy the Afcioeiatad Praia.\nRepresentative Kineheloe, Democrat,\nKentucky, today sent his resignation as\na member of Congress to Gov. Sampson\nof Kentucky, to become effective Octo\nber 9, when he will take oSce as a\nmember of the Federal Customs Court.\nKineheloe also sent his resignation as\na Democratic nominee for Congress in\nthe second Kentucky district to the\nsecretary of State in Kentucky, thereby\nremoving his name from the ballot at\nthe forthcoming elections.\nA special election must be held to\nselect a successor to complete Kinche\nloe\u2019s unexpired term.\nThe Kentuckian aald he was resign\ning immediately at the request of Presi\ndent Hoover, who named him to the\nCustoms Court and asked him to take\noffice on October 8, when the Pall\nterm of the court opens.\nBOGUS BILLS REPORTED\nSecret Service Warn* Public of Two\nNew Counterfeits.\nChief W. H. Moran of the United\nStates Secret Service today warned the\npublic against two new counterfeit bills.\nThey are described briefly as follows: A\n430 bill on the Federal Reserve Bank of\nCleveland, Ohio, 1928 series, check let\nter \u201cI,\" face plate No. 22, back plate\nnumber Indistinct, probably 107; H. T.\nTate, Treasurer of the United States;\nA. W. Mellon, Secretary of the Treas\nury; portrait of Jackson.\nA 45 bill on the Federal Reserve Bank\nof Boston, Mass.; 1928 series, check let\nter \u201cL,\" lace plate No. 8, back plate\nNo. 3: H. T. Tate, Treasurer of the\nUnited States; A. W. Mellon, Secretary\nof the Treasury; portrait of Lincoln.\nEndurance Test for Eadio Voice.\nNEW YORK, September 27\nNorman Pearce, radio announcer, seems\nto have quite a voice from the endur\nance standpoint. He talked Into a mike\nfor 24 hours straight at a radio fair on\nvarious things from capital punishment\nto the South Sea Islands.\nlord mayor, said: \u201cThe ties which exist\nbetween Ulster and the United States\nare many and varied. We recall with\npride the names of eminent men from\nthis little province who played a noble\npart in shaping the deetlniee of the\ngreat nation whoee Ambassador is with\nus today. I believe no fewer than 10\nPresidents of the United States were\ndescendants of Ulster stock.\u201d\nGen. Dawes will spend the week and\nin Northern Ireland, returning to Lon\ndon Tuesday\nTHE EVEXiyft STAB, WASHINGTON, D. C.. SATURDAY. SEPTEMBER 27. M\nJONES* TITLE\nIN AMATEUR GOLF\nDefeats Gene Homans, 8 Up,\nMaking Sweep of Major\nHonors for Year.\nFrom First Page.)\nsecond shots just reached the green,\nwith Homans' slightly away. Gene\u2019s\napproach putt was short, so wm Bob's.\nJones holed hla 4. Homans got his\nhalf.\nJones 3 up.\nSeventh hole. 355 yards, par 4\nJtmes drove to the edge of a ditch and\npitched on. Homans had a straight\ndrive and aant a good second well, putt\ning from 29 feet. Bob ran up close\nfrom 20 feat. Gene was within a foot\nand atymiad Jones. Bob could not get\nby hie opponent's ball and took 5 to 4\n1 for Homans.\nJonas 3 up.\ni It was Homans\u2019 first hole.\nI Eighth hole, 350 yards, par 4\u2014There\nwas little to choose between the drives\nand they pitched well on. Each putted\nclose and it was a half in 4\u2019s.\nJones 2 up.\nNinth hole\u2014Jones pitched on from\nthe tea at the short ninth, while Gene\ndrova in water and took a penalty\nstroke. Jones was down in par 3 to 4\nl tor Homans.\nJones 3 up.\nI The card (morning):\nJones, out 46355454 3\u201439\nHomans, out... 56469444 4\u201443\nTenth hole, 335 yards, par 4.\u2014Ho\nmans hooked to rough from the tea\nafter Jones sent a long one down the\nfairway. Jones played safely to the\nmiddle of the green. Gene\u2019s ball rolled\nto a trap beyond the green. He ex\nploded far past the pin and then putted\nelose. Bob was down in 3 putts for\nhis par 4 and went 4 up.\nEleventh hole, 373 yards, par 4.\nPreferring accuracy to distance, Jones\nwas driving with a spoon. The tee\nshots at the eleventh were not far apart\nbut Homans was in front again. Bob\nplayed for the middle of the green and\nwas 25 feet from the pin. Homans\npitched within eight feat. Jones holed\nthe long putt for a birdie 3. Homans\njust missed his putt and took a par 4.\nJones 5 up.\nTwelfth hale, 415 yards, par 4\u2014Jones\nhad the longer ball at the twefth, but\nwas not in the beat position to approach\nthe elevated green. Homans hit a low,\nrakish shot to the green. Jones pitched\nhigh, and the balls were about equi?\ndistant from the cup. about 35 feet. Bob\npitched dose, and Gene just missed. It\nwas a half in par 4. Jones 5 up.\nThirteenth hole, 125 yards, par 3\u2014.\nBoth tee shots were on the edge of the\ngreen on the side of which the cup was\nplaced. Homans putted from 12 feet. 2\nfeet past the cup. From 10 feet Jones\njust missed. They holed par 3s. Jones\n5 up.\nFourteenth hole, 412 yards; par\nfour\u2014The drives again at the four\nteenth were close together, with Gene\naway. Homans hit a spoon second shot\nto the left of the green. Bob was on\nwith a No. 9 iron, la feet from the cup\nand pulled to the lip. Homans was\nseven feet short in 3 and barely missed\nhis 4, taking a 5. Jones took par 4 and\nwent 6 up.\nFifteenth hole, 270 yards; par four\u2014\nJones was away from the tee, but was\nsix feet from the pin. Gene\u2019s second\ncaught the aide of a trap and rolled to\nthe sand. Qane came out and missed\nhis putt for a 4, conceding the hole.\nJones knocked his putt for the\nbirdie 3. Jones 7 up.\nSixteenth hole, 435 yards, par 4\nAgain at the sixteenth the \u201cquarry\nhole,\u201d there was no appreciable ad\nvantage in the drives. Homans sent a\nhigh iron over the cavern to the green.\nJones with a No. 4 iron was well Inside\nfrom 60 feet Gene putted 4 feet short.\nJones\u2019 putt lipped the cup. Homans\nmissed and took 5 to par 4 for Jones\nSeventeenth hole, 315 yards, par 3\nJones\u2019 tee shot carried to thick rough\nat the left. Homans drove within 7\nfeet of the cup. Jones approached to\nwithin 9 feet and missed tha putt, tak\ning 4 to a birdie 2 for Homans. Jonas 7\nup.\nEighteenth hole, 448 yards, par 4\nBoth drove to rough at the left at the\nhome hole. Jonea was slightly in front.\nHomans was over the green with a long\niron. Jones pitched 18 feet from the\npin. Gene\u2019s third was too strong and\nha waa atill away. Ha holed the 20-foot\nputt for the par 4. Jonaa just mlssad\nand it was a half in par 4.\nCards:\nSlonjans, in.. 54435592 4\u201437\u201479\nonas, in.... 4 9434944 4\u201433\u201472\nNineteenth hole, 380 yards; par, 4.\nJones again drove with a spoon and was\na few yards behind Homans' tee shot,\nwhich reached a shallow trap. Bob\nwas just short of the green with his\nsecond, while Homans was cm. Jones\nran up dead and Homans putted close.\nIt was a half in par 4. Jones 7 up.\nTwentieth hole, 523 yards; par, 5.\nGene's tee was in an adjoining fair\nway at the long twentieth. Bob was\nin the clear. Both ware short in two,\nbut Jones put his third 10 feet from\nthe pin. Homans\u2019 third went over and\nhe putted short. Jones misted and the\nhole was halved in par 5. Jones, 7 up.\nTwenty-first hole, 195 yards; par. 3.\n\u2014Neither reached the short twenty-first\nfrom the tee. Jones almost holed out\nfrom a trap. Homans was just on the\nedge of the green. Gene slipped 2 feet\npast the cup on his first effort and\nleft himself a partial stymie. He missed\nthe putt and took 4 to 3 for Jones.\nJones going 8 up.\nTwenty-second hole, 595 yards; par.\ns.\u2014Homans was trapped from the tee\nat the long twenty-second and Jonea\nNEW CONNECTING LINK BETWEEN U. S. AND CANADA\n\n1 hk\nTim\nI BMMriia g A\nInterior el the new Detroit, Mich.-Windsor, Ontario, Canada, vehicular tunnel, which will be opened in November.\n\u2014Wide World Photo.\nFIVE DIE AS GALE\nSINKS LAKE COATS\nTwo Go Down Off Michigan,\nWhile Fate of Third\nIs Undetermined.\nBy the Associated Press.\nMUSKEGON. Mich., September 27.\nThe waters of Lake Michigan, whip\nped into a fury by a 40-mile gale yes\nterday, took the lives of at least five\npersons, swallowed up two boats and\nleft the fate of a third undetermined\nthis morning.\nThe five dead were members of the\ncrew es the barge Salvor, caught in the\ngale yesterday afternoon when less\nthan 2 miles from safety in the harbor\nhere.\nNine others of the fourteen who were\naboard the barge reached shore alive.\nTwo of them were brought in this\nmorning after having spent 16 hours\nlashed to the derrick on the barge.\nThey were taken to Grand Haven by\nmembers of the Coast Guard crew from\nthat point, who shot a line aboard the\nbarge to rescue them. A third man\nlashed to the derrick was dead and be\ncause of th\u00ab heavy seas still running\nefforts to remove tiie body were aban\ndoned.\nTwo bodies, those of Lornie Olmstead.\n9 yean old. and Elmer Lytie of Detour.\nMich., already have come ashore. The\nbody left on the barge was that of\nClinton Lane of Muskegon. The two\nmissing are Clarenet Barnett and Tony\nWlnaerowski of Muskegon.\nTwo in Serious Condition.\nThe survivors are Mrs. Ida Olmstead.\nmother of Lomie, employed as a cook:\nher sister, Alice la Plaunt. cook; Onnrv\nla Plaunt. all of Sault Ste. Marie; Ed\nward Winserowski pf Detour. Floyd\nO'Connor, George Secord, Clement\nShurage and Lyman Nedeau. all of\nMuskegon, and Harry Smith of Newark,\nN. J.\nNedqau and Smith were the two\ntaken off the barge this morning. After\nthe Coast Guard had taken them to\nGrand Haven, it was decided to bring\nthem back here to a hospital. They\nwere in a eerious condition from ex\nposure. Throughout the night waves\nhad dashed over them as they were\ntied to the derrick.\nThe other vessel to go down before\nthe gale was the echooner Our Son.\nlast of hej type on the lakes. She\nfoundered off LUdlngton, Mich., her\ncrew of seven being removed by the\nfreighter William Nelson.\nThird Boat Unreported.\nA third boat, the steel-hulled motor\ncarrier North Shore, which left 6t.\nJoseph. Mich., with a cargo of grapes\nyesterday morning en route to Mil\nwaukee, had not been reported today.\nShe carried five men and a woman.\nFears for the safety of eight mem\nbers of the Coast Guard crew from\nLudington, who set out at 4 p m. yes\nterday to go to the aid of the schooner,\nwere dispelled this morning when word\nwas received here that they had reached\nSheboygan. Wls., making the crossing\nunder their own power.\nThe passenger ship Missouri arrived\nat Muskegon last night several hours\noverdue from Milwaukee, after battling\nheavy seas. Fear had been expressed\nfor its safety because of the strong\ngale which had been raging and be\ncause nothing had been heard from it.\nwas in the rough. Homans was short\nof the green in 3 and on in 4, 40 feet\nfrom the pin. Jones pitched 12 feet\nfrom the eup In 3. Homans was down\nin 9. Jones holed his par 5 and went\n9 up.\nTwenty-third hole, 435 yards; par,\n4.\u2014The drives at the twenty-third were\nnot far apart. Jones was in front 12\nyards. Each second shot found a rest\ning place on the green. Jones 50 feet\nfrom the cup, Homans, 38. Jones\u2019 putt\nwas 4 feet short. It was a half in par 4.\nJones, 9 up.\nTwenty-fourth hole, 442 yards, par 4\n\u2014The drives were close together, 230\nand 250 yards down the fairway at the\ntwenty-fourth. Homans used a spoon to\nget home in two. Jones took a No. 3\niron. They were both home with Jones\nwell Inside. Homan* putted elose from\n50 feet So did Jones. They halved in\npar 4s. Jones 9 up.\nTwenty-fifth hole, 355 yards, par 4\nHomans was in the fairway while Jones\ndrove to rough. Their seconds rolled\npast the pin, and each had good putts\nleft for their pars. They missed and\nhalved in ss.\nTwenty-sixth hole, 350 yards, par 4\nBob nearly drove the green and chipped\nto 10 feet of the cup. Homans was too\nstrong with his approach, but just\nmissed sinking a 15-footer. It was a\nhalf in 4*.\nTwenty-seventh hole. 170 yards, par\n3\u2014Jones missed the green with his tee\nshot at the twenty-seventh and went\ninto a trap. Homans was 10 feet from\nthe cup. Jones was 18 feet short in 2\nand was down in 4, conceding Homans\nhis putt and the hole. Jones 8 up.\nCards afternoon:\nHomans\u2014\nOut 454844(4 2\u2014lt\nJones-\nOut 45354454 4\u201435\nTwenty-eighth hole, 335 yards, par 4\n\u2014Jones drove a very long ball, but- in\nrough. Homans was in the fairway, 30\nyards behind. Gene put his aeoond in\na trap to the left. Jones' second found\nthe same trap. Bob failed to get out\non his third and took 4 to reach the\ngreen, 15 feet from the pin. Gene went\nover the green to a trap on the other\nside In 4. They were about the same\ndistanee from the cup. It was a half\nin 6s and Jones was dormie 8.\nTWO NOBKISES AT NEBRASKA CAMPAIGN QUIZ\n\u00bbm a\u00bb vnA MMMLML.ig:.<>. -R,fv: f.| ASZmKmKZ\nwH. a VHL dK\u00df(B\u00dfiw\u00df3Bw%B 'lfc's v II issalsisS'\nK1 g^\niHI 43^*^\naBy<gWfCTjHBBMaBIBBBBBaHMft m,_ y r\n\nGrorer Georce W. Norris of Broken Bow, Nebr. (seated at end of table, wearing bow tie), and Senator George W. Nor\nris met at the Senates Campaign Fund Investigation Committee hearing in Lincoln, Nebr. The committee Inauired\nInto the filing of Grocer Norris as a primary candidate against Senator Norris. His name was barred from the ballot by\na Supreme Court ruling. Senator Norris is shown at the extreme right. \u2014Associated Press Photo.\nREWARDS POSTED\nFOR CAPONE MEN\n35 Chicago Detectives to Be\nTransferred as Result of\n\u201cCensorship.\u201d\nBy the Associated Brass.\nCHICAGO, September 37.\u2014The \"Ca\npone censorship\u201d of the Police Depart\nment had riled Police Commissioner\nAieoek to determined action today.\nThirty-five members of the Detective\nBureau will be removed and the bureau\nreorganised, the commissioner said, in\nan effort to cheek wholesale gang\nespionage within the police ranks.\nThe commissioner particularly want*\nto know how the confidential list of\ngangsters to be hunted down as va\ngrants got from the Detective Bureau to\na room at the Carleen Hotel occupied\nby a Capone bondsman. The list was\nfound by Federal agents in a raid\nThursday.\nEight Names Omitted.\nHe wants to know, too, the meaning\nof tits penciled crosses in front of\neight names on the confidential list.\nThe eight names were of well known\nworker# in the ranks of A1 Capon*.\nEspecially perplexing, however, was the\nfact that copies of the list, when com\npared at police headquarters, showed\nthe eight names had been omitted.\nThe explanation at the Detective\nBureau is that the police officer who\nput down the original list of names\u2014\nthe one found by the Federal raiders\u2014\nhad later made his copies from memory\nafter realising that the original had\ndisappeared. Commissioner Aloock. how\never, wants to know why, in copying\nfrom memory, the police officer left\noff the same names *a those designated\nby crosses on the list the Federal men\nfound in the possession of the Capone\nbondsman.\nOffer g1,\u00ab06 Reward.\nBusiness men today lent additional\naid to the police effort to smash the\ngang syndicate grip on Chicago by of.\nsering a reward of BLOOO for the ar\nrest of Frank Nitti, a Capone execu\ntive. Nltti is under Federal indictment\nfor income tax fraud. Similar action\nis anticipated in the case of Jake Ou\nsiek, \u201ccollector\" and \u201cpay-off\u201d man for\nthe Capone group, who also faees Oov.\neminent aetion.\nThe Association of Commerce, which\n3ffered the reward, said it had been told\nby Federal officials that Nitti is now\nthe aetual head of the gang, of whieh\nCapone is merely the figurehead.\nCity Htnaggrg Re-elect Storey.\nSAN FRANCISCO, September 37 (Jf).\n\u2014Stephen B. Storey. Rochester, N. Y.,\nwaa re-elected president of the Inter\nnational City Managers' Association\nyesterday.\nBAND CONCERT.\nBy the United States Soldiers' Home\nMilitary Band, this evening at 6:30\no\u2019clock. John 8. M. Zimmerman, band\nmuter; Anton Pointner, assistant.\nMarch. \"V- S. Field Artillery\u201d.. .Sousa\nOverture, \u201cSakuntala\" Ooldmark\nXylophone solos\u2014\nThe Waterfall\u201d stebbe\n\u201cPopular Medley.\u201d\nGrand Pantasia, \u201cSongs of\nScotland\u201d Lampo\nPox trot. \u201cI Kiss Your Hand,\nMadame\" Erwin\nWalts Suite, \"Polio Ivresse\". Waldteufel\nFinale\u2014-\n\u201cThe Trumpeters\u2019 Carnival\u201d.. Lescy\n\u2022The Star Spangled Banner.\u201d\nThu will conclude the series of out\ndoor concerts for the season. Orches\ntral concerts will begin on October 14,\nat 8:30 o'clock, in Stanley Hall.\nCandidate Chopping\nWood for Vote Told\nRival Churns for It\nB; the AiioeUtad Press.\nFRANKLIN, N. C., September\n37.\u2014Bert Slagle is Democratic\ncandidate for sheriff in this\ncounty.\nBam Franks is Republican can\ndidate for the same office.\nSlagle, out on the hustings,\nnoted a woman chopping wood.\nHe offered his help. An nour he\nchopped wood, while ths perspira\ntion poured off.\nAt last the wood was eut and\nSlagle seated himself on the front\nporch to rest. The question of his\ncandidacy came up.\n\u201cI hardly know who to vote\nfor,\u201d the lady said. \"Both you\nand Mr. Franks have been so nice\nto us.\n\"Why right now Mr. Franks is\nout on the back porch churning.\u201d\nREPUBLICAN SPLIT\nTO AIDROOSEVELT\nAnti-Saloon League Seen as\nThorn in Side for Tuttle\nin Campaign.\nBY DAVID LAWRENCE.\nWhile the Republicans of New York\nState, by the adoption of a wet plank\nin the gubernatorial campaign, have\nendeavored to neutralise the advantage\nthat the Democrats have enjoyed in the\nEmpire state for the last decade, the\nnet effect of a split In the Republican\nParty way mean th* continuance In\nOflfSe off3ov. Roosevelt, Democrat.\nDetermination of the dry* to punish\ntheir Republican brethren by putting\na third party tieket in th* field is in\nline with the taetica pursued in Illin\nois and In other States. The Anti-\nSaloon League recognises that it might\nmean the election of a Democratic wet,\nbut their reasoning 1* that the Demo\n\u201catlc party having gone wet, the Re\npublican party cannot be permitted to\nfollow the same course, especially since\nhundreds of thousands of Republican\nvoters from the rural districts are at\ntached to the dry cause.\nFallowed Cox Speech.\nIs significant that the Republican\nState platform In New York follows\nalmost exactly the ideas laid down by\nformer Oov. Cox of Ohio in hi* key\nnote speech in Columbus, Ohio, last\nJune when he pointed out that Dwight\nMorrow's platform in New Jersey did\nnot close the door against the saloon\nand outline a conception of repeal of\ne rtfhteenth amendment which the\nRepublicans now have recognised is a\nstronger argument than to point no\nspecific alternative to the eighteenth\namendment.\nThere is no doubt that the action of\nthe Republican state Convention in\nNew York is a disappointment to dry\nt\u00a3\u00ab er i,. beca use of national atten-\nS\u00a3\" l*ve\u00bb to everything done in the\nEmpire State. The battle this year.\nthat* wh'iei? 2 0t muc j 1 different from\ndeveloped when Senator\nj candidate for re-\nR nd advocated the repeal of\namendment.\nnubi\u00a3im d T\u00a3/! n L. an independent Re\npublican and took away enough votes\n\u201cj\u2122 1 Wadsworth to enable a Demo-\nWhen the argument is\nL 4 5Sf atratecy merely added a\nthat thl \u2018riJSET\"? dry answered\nthat the election of Wadsworth would\nhave meant the same thing, but that it\nJ a L\"YL re important to keep the dry\nparty on the dry side of the argument\nby asserting in the election the veto\npower of dry votes.\nLeague Net Concerned.\nT campaign in New\nYork State has even less significance\nso far as a possible vote on wet or dry\nlaws because it ia not likely that any\nFederal amendment will be submitted to\nthe State Legislature in the next two\nyears and also with the wet sentiment\npreponderant no issue is expected to\narise on any State enforcement laws.\nSo the Anti-Saloon League isn't con\ncerned very much whether a Republi\ncan wet or a Democratic wet hold* the\noffice of Governor.\nA third tieket in the field will be a\nthorn in the side of Charles Tuttle,\nthe Republican nominee for Governor,\nespecially since he has achieved con\nsiderable strength by his attacks on\nTammany Hall, and the race might be\nclose If an Independent Republican did\nnot draw tens of thousands of vo\u2019et\nfrom Mr. Tuttle. It all depends on\nwho the Anti-Saloon League and the\ndry organization put up for Governor.\nPublished report* have mentioned\nFrank E. Gannett of Rochester, who\nown# a string of newspapers in several\ncities of New York State, and who is\na pronounced dry. He would have the\ncordial support of the dry organiza\ntions if ha could be persuaded to run.\nHe has not been active in party poli\ntics before, but his nomination would\ncost Mr. Tuttle a good many votes.\nBetween Two Desires.\nN e w York State has always been wet\nand the Republican party has been torn\nbetween two desires\u2014one, to placate the\nrural elements which are dry, and. two,\nto make inroads in the big cities, where\nthe Democrats have been able to raise\nthe wet issue and thus take control of\nthe Btate government almost uninter\nruptedly since the eighteenth amend\nment was sdopted.\nThe tact that the State platform pro\nposes repeal of the eighteenth amend\nment was hailed by wet leaders as the\ngreatest advance they had made toward\nbreaking down the strangle hold the\ndrys have had on the Republican sarty\nthroughout the eountiy.\n(CODTrlfht, 1130.)\nSEYMOUR TO FACE\nPERJURY CHARGES\nIN NORRIS PROBE\n(Continued From First I\nto the second George W. Norris end his\nlater connection with the Republican\nSenatorial Campaign Committee. I\nalso take into account the fact that W.\nE. Murray, who was on the pay roll\nof the Republican National Commit*\ntee, was in Nebraska and made a sur\nvey before the Republican primary.\u201d\nNye said A. Paul Johnson, a Broken\nBow lawyer, had testified he delivered\na SSOO Liberty bond to Grocer Norris at\nthe time he filed as a candidate.\n\u201cIt is assumed,\" said Nye, \u201cthat this\nbond was received from Seymour,\u201d\nSeymour told the committee in July\nhe had never seen the Broken Bow\nNorris and had no relations with him.\nLater Seymour was appointed vice\nchairman of the Republican Senatorial\nCommittee in the West and yesterday\nhe resigned that office \u201cfor the good of\nthe party\u201d after the Senate Committee\nhearings in Nebraska.\nSEYMOUR QUITS G. O. F. POST.\nParty Aide Resigns After Part in Norris\nCampaign Is Charged.\nBy tbs Associated Press.\nDENVER, Colo., September 27.\u2014Re\nverberations of the dual Morris Repub\nlican senatorial candidacies todsy pres\naged the probable exit of Victor Bey\nmour, Lincoln business man, from the\nWestern political picture.\nSeymour, lately appointed assistant\nvies chairman of the Western Repub\nlican political campaign, yaaterday tel\negraphed his resignation to Senator\nFrederick Steiwer of Oregon. In his\ntelegram Seymour Insisted that, while\nhe was \u201cabsolutely Innocent of any\nwrong act\u201d in connection with the Ne\nbraska primary controversy, he was act\ning solely from a desire to keep the\npublicity attending the committee hear\ning! of Senator Gerald P, Nye in Ne\nbraska from reflecting on the party'!\nsenatorial committee.\nFirst Denied Charges.\nWhether Seymour's resignation would\nbe accepted was not announced today,\nbut it was a consensus of party lead\ners here that it would be.\nAt McCook. Nebr\u201e Senator George\nNorris said he understood Senators\nNye and Porter H. Hale of the Senate\nCampaign Funds Investigating Com\nmittee had recommended Seymour\u2019s\nremoval.\nSeymour\u2019s name figured In the Nye\nhearing at Lincoln soon after his ar\nrival here. He immediately denied hs\nknew anything about the candidacy of\nGeorge W. Norrle, \u201cthe second,\" a\ngrocer of Broken Bow, Nebr., whose\nfiling for the nomination to the offloe\nheld by Senator Norris was thrown out\nbecause it was made too late. \u201cThe\naffair is Greek to me,\u201d Seymour said\nwhen hs was Informed Senator Nye had\nannounced perjury charges would be\nfiled against \u201ccertain persons\" as a\nresult of testimony given at the Lin\ncoln hearing.\nDenise the Charge.\nBefore eoming to Colorado, Seymour\nappeared before the Nye Committee and\ndenied he knew anything about the\ncandidacy of the Broken Bow grocer\nNorria \"the second\u201d at first told the\ncommittee he attempted to enter the\nrace on his own volition, but later\nchanged hie testimony to say Seymour\npaid his SSO filing fee.\nA f\u00bb\u00abl Johnaon, Broken Bow attor\nney, testified Seymour paid the mipg\nfee and said he \u201cassumed\u201d Seymour\nhad sent a SSOO bond which was given\nto Grocer Norria after he had filed\nfor the nomination.\nAlthough declining to comment at\nlength on his telegraphic resignation\npending the return of Senator Steiwer\nfrom Oregon thia week, Seymour told\nnewspaper men he had acted \"entirely\non my own volition and without having\nysffSsS* on\u00df 1 thlnk 1\nLUCIEN W. POWELL, 84,\nDIES IN SANITARIUM\nAFTER LONG ILLNESS\n(Continued From First Page\nLewis Helakell of Washington and Mrs.\nFrances MUlott of Wlndber, Pa., daugh\nters, and Lucien Fitzhugh Powell of\nWashington.\nMany of the artist\u2019s paintings are to\nbe found in Washington. but a large\nnumber are distributed throughout the\nJL orl L Perr anent exhibitions are in\nthe Public Library, Congressional Club\nAmerican University and Georgetown\nUniversity, which has a holy land col\nlection. Mrs. Henderson possesses\n20\u00b0 of bis paintings, which com-\np the largest private collection.\nrt-3 e Afterglo f\u00a3 Picture of the\nOrand Canyon of the Colorado, now in\nthe Corcoran Gallery, and his painting,\n\u2022Grand Canyon of the Yellowstone\nwhich hangs in the National\nArt Gallery, are especially well known.\nThe Atlanta Museum of Art has a col\nlection of his paintings. London art\nbrokers distributed Mr. Powell\u2019s work\nto such advantage that he said on one\noccasion that \u201cthe sun never sets\u2019* on\nhis pictures.\nNative of Virginia.\nKnown as a resident of Washington.\nMr. Powell was a native of Virginia, and\nmuch of hie work was done at hie home\nin Loudoun County. He was born De\ncember IS, l\u00ab\u00ab$, at Levinworth Manor,\nVa.. the estate of hie father, John Levin\nPowell.\nAt 17 he fought In the Confederate\nArmy with his brothers and after the\nCivil War journeyed to Philadelphia to\nstudy painting under Thomas Moran,\nmaster of canyon pictures. His studies\ntoot him to New York, Paris and Lon\ndon, and In later years to Italy and\nthe Holy Land. In his travels he added\ncolor to his work, but he alwaya re\ngarded himself as an American painter\nof American subjects.\nPresident Roosevelt was one of the i\nfirst to re cognize the worth of hie work\n1932 WET PLANK\nQUESTION RAISED\nRecent Developments in Both\nParties Cause Leaders\nto Ponder Issue.\nBY FRANCIS M. STEPHEN SQN,\nAssociated Press Stsflt Wri'tr.\nWith prohibition persistently bobbing\nup in polities this year, national party\nleaders are wondering if this issue is to\nbe drawn in the 1912 presidential cam\npaign.\nIn other words, the political leaders\nare wondering if either of the two na\ntional parties will adopt a wet plank\ntwo years hence for the first time since\nadoption of the eighteenth amendment,\nand whether either will nominate a wet\ncandidate.\nPresident Hoover supported the eight\neenth amendment in his 102$ race. and\nAlfred E. Smith ran as a wet, but the\nDemocratic platform was not wet. Mr.\nHoover declared against repeal of the\neighteenth amendment and, in effect,\nagainst modification.\nMr. Hoover\u2019s utterances are regarded\nas putting the Republican party in the\ndry column nationally, but the ranks of\nboth the Republicans and Democrats\nare divided on this question. The New\nYoik State Republicans have declared\ntor repeal, as has Dwight W. Morrow,\nRepublican senatorial nominee in New\nJersey.\nUw Beard Report Awaited.\nMeanwhile, as the Republican admin-\nWtration waits for the report of the Law\nEnforcement Commission on ite inquiry\nof prohibition, Democrats are speculat\ning on what effect the declarations of\nOo\u00a3 Roosevelt of New York and James\nA. Retd of Missouri tor prohibition re\npeal will have on tha next Democratic\nconvention. Both are viewed as presi\ndential possibilities.\nChairman Tydings of the Democratic\nSenatorial Campaign Committee has de\nclared prohibition an issue in many of\nfS* this year, and most of\nthe Democratic senatorial candidates in\nthe North and Bast are running to wets,\nwith wet planks in a number of State\nplatforms. Chairman Raakob of the\nDemocratic National Committee is for\nrepeal.\nBu t the Democratic stronghold of\nthe Southland Is dry, and if a wet\nplank gets Into the next Democratic\nplatform it will be over the determined\nopposition of this section of the party.\nSenator Robinson of Arkansas, who\nrecently was renominated and who has\nbeen advanced by his state tor the\nDemocratic presidential nomination, is\n\u00bbvowed advocate of national prohi\nbition.\nHoover Quoted on Views.\nIn view of the recent prohibition out\nbreaks and the prospect of action by\nthe Law Enforcement Commission on\nthis subject, political leaders have locked\nover President Hoover\u2019* views on pro\nhibition. Her* is what he said when\nhe wrote to Senator Borah, Republican.\nIdaho, in Is2B as a candidate tor the\nRepublican nomination and what he\nrepeated when he accepted that noml\nnation:\n\u201cI do not favor the repeal of the\neighteenth amendment. I stand for\nthe efficient enforcement of the laws\nenacted thereunder. Whoever is ehoaen\nPresident has under his oath the solemn\nduty to pursue this course.\ni \u201cOur country has deliberately under*\nr taken a great social and economic\nexperiment, noble in motive and far\nreaching in purpoee. It must be worked\ni out constructively.\u201d\nHe added, in his speech of aceeptanoe,\n\u201cModification of the enforcement laws\ni which would permit that which the\nConstitution forbids is nullification.\nThis the American people will not coun\ntenance-\u201d\ni National Republican leaders are silent\n1 on the news from Albany that the New\nState convention adopted a repeal\nP Dry* belittle the effect of the move,\nand those of the Republican faith pre\n-1 dieted It would have no bearing on the\nnext national convention of the party.\ni Stinson Talk Omits Subject.\nSecretary Stimson, head of Preti- v\ndent Hoover\u2019s cabinet, delivered the key\nnote address to the New York State\nConvention, but he said nothing on the\nsubject of prohibition.\nMany here conceded that the con\ni version of the New York Republican\norganisation to the cause of prohibition\nrepeal would be likely to bring this issue\nbefore the next National Convention,\nbut Senator Brookhart of lowa, a Re\npublican dry, predicted President Hoover\nwould \u201ckeep the party dry,\u201d and. he\nadded, \u201cWall Street will lie down to\nhim.\u201d\nBrookhart said. \u201cWe haven\u2019t lost a\nthing\u201d because the New York Repub\nlicans had adopted the repeal platform.\nHe said Bantor Wadsworth, a Repub\nlican. had run a* a wet In New York\nin Is2s, \u2018and he is ex-Senator Wads\nworth now.\u201d\nSenator Sheppard, Democrat, Texas,\nanother dry, said the New York Re\npublican wetness \u201chas no material sig\nnificance.\u201d He believed \u2018it Just reflects\nthe wet sentiment of New York City,\n\u00bbhich has always been wet.\u201d\nBrookhart recalled that the New York\nRepublicans, led by former Senstor\nWadsworth and Nicholas Murray But\nler. president of Columbia University,\nhad urged a wet plank unsuccessfully\nat the last Republican National Con\nvention.\nChairman Feu of the Republican\nNational Committee and Senator Wat\naon of Indiana, Republican leeder In\nthe Senate, withheld comment on the\nNew York action.\nWith the Hoover administration tak\ning no part In the wet and dry con\ntroversy, interested continued to center\non the forthcoming report of the Law\nEnforcement Commission, which has\nbeen studying the prohibition situation.\nLondon's Remedy for Traffic Jams.\nLONDON, September 27 {IP). \u2014Track-\nleu trolleys tor some London suburbs\nare proposed by the Royal Commission\nof Transport as a means of ending con\ngestion. Hundreds of miles of track\nwould be pulled up.\nand he became one of a group of ad\nmirers which in years to come were\nto include many prominent men and\nwomen in this country and abroad.\nThe Powell family Is of Welch origin.\nThe Uandgollen estate at Upperviu*.\nVa., was gran tad to the family by the\nKing of England about 1770, There,\nin the historic hunting region, the\nPowells entertained George Washington\nand Lafayette on the 10,000-acre es\ntate. The artist\u2019a uncle, Cuthbert\nPowell, made it his home for many\nysare. and today the house which\nWashington and Lafayette knew stands\non 1.000 acres of the original tract.\n..Thru years ago 85 members of the\n\u2018Powell clan\u201d gathered at the estate\ntor a family reunion and the distin\nguished artist member delivered an ad*\ndreu. Last Spring the property passed\nfrom the family to the ownership of\nJohn Hay Whitney, the grandson of the\nformer Secretary of State, and yester\nday Mr. Whitney took his bride, the\ntormer Mlu Elizabeth Altemus of\nPhiladelphia, to the estate which he\nh*d obtained as a bridal gift.\nWas Godly Maa.\nMr. Powell did not have good health\nas a youth but he overcame this physical\nhandicap. On the occasion or his\ntlghty-flm birthday anniversary he\nsaid In an Interview that he had had\n\"a very wonderful life.\"\nHe commented that he was a Godly ft\nman. \u201cGod,\u201d he said, \u201cexists in color,\nin love and in goodness.\u201d Throughout\nhis travels, he said, he had been Im\npressed by\u201c God's mighty work in\nmountains and sea, in all things shoe\ning His handiwork in flowers and land\nscapes and His goodness added to all\nthis.\u201d","height":"25455","width":"19791"}}
